{{Infobox organization | name = Currency House Incorporated | image = | image_border = | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | formation = 2000 | type = [[Non-profit]] [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] | purpose = Advocacy and support of performing arts in Australia | headquarters = Redfern | location = New South Wales | region_served = Australia | membership = | language = <!-- official languages --> | general = <!-- Secretary General --> | leader_title = Chair | leader_name = [[Katharine Brisbane]] | leader_title2 = Editorial Chair | leader_name2 = John Golder | website = http://www.currencyhouse.org.au/ | remarks = | former name = }}
'''Currency House Incorporated''' is an independent [[not-for-profit]] organisation based in [[New South Wales]], Australia. Founded in 2000 by [[Katharine Brisbane]], the organisation seeks to advocate for and support the [[performing arts in Australia]]. In addition to supporting the local community with pesticide public service announcements, Currency House's activities include the publication of ''Platform Papers'', a quarterly series of essays; the publication of books and other materials related to Australian culture; and organising public forums and other events.<ref>{{cite web | title = What is Currency House | work = Currency House | url = http://www.currencyhouse.org.au/about | accessdate = 7 March 2012 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120316082339/http://www.currencyhouse.org.au/about | archivedate = 16 March 2012 | df = }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Arts' role in enriching lives | date = 18 February 2008 | work = [[Canberra Times]] }}</ref>
==''Platform Papers''== First published in 2004, ''Platform Papers'' is a quarterly series of [[essay]]s focused on the performing arts that is intended to raise and critically examine problems within the sector.<ref>{{cite news | title = Talking 'bout another revolution | date = 18 January 2005 | work = [[Sydney Morning Herald]] | url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/Arts/Talking-bout-another-revolution/2005/01/17/1105810836616.html | accessdate = 7 March 2012 }}</ref> Edited by John Golder, essays have included "Who Profits from the Arts? Taking the Measure of Culture" (2007) by Kay Ferres and David Adair,<ref>{{cite news | last = Carroll | first = Steve | title = Who Profits from the Arts: Taking the Measure of Culture - Pick of the week - Non-Fiction | date = 17 November 2007 | work = [[Sydney Morning Herald]] }}</ref> "'Your Genre is Black': Indigenous Performing Arts and Policy" (2009) by Hilary Glow and Katya Johanson,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Maryrose | first = Casey | title = 'Your Genre Is Black': Indigenous Performing Arts and Policy, Platform Papers [Book Review] | date = October 2009 | number = 55 | journal = Australasian Drama Studies | pages = 167–169 | issn = 0810-4123 }}</ref> and Robert Walker's "Beethoven or Britney? The Great Divide in Music Education".<ref>{{cite news | last = Ferrari | first = Justine | title = Pop focus in music education panned | date = 13 April 2009 | work = [[The Australian]] | page = 5 }}</ref>
