{{italic title}}
'''''India Becoming''''' is a book by author [[Akash Kapur]]. The book is an account of change and transformation in modern India. It was selected by ''[[The New Yorker]]'' and ''[[The New Republic]]'' as a Best Book of 2012,<ref name="NewYorkerBestBooks">{{cite news | last = | first = | coauthors = | title =Best Books of 2012 | newspaper =The New Yorker| location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =13 December 2012 | url =http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/books/2012/12/best-books-of-2012.html | accessdate =21 May 2013 }}</ref><ref name="Newyorkerbestbooks">{{cite news | last = | first = | coauthors = | title =New Republic Editor and Writer Picks: Best Books of 2012 | newspaper =New Republic| location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =26 December 2012 | url =https://newrepublic.com/article/111113/new-republic-editor-and-writer-picks-best-books-2012# | accessdate =21 May 2013 }}</ref> and ''[[Newsweek]]'' as one of its three Must Reads on Modern India.<ref name="DailyBeastMustReads">{{cite news | last =Verger | first =Rob | coauthors = | title =Three Must-Reads On Modern India | newspaper =The Daily Beast| location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =24 September 2012 | url =http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/09/23/three-essential-reads-on-modern-india.html | accessdate =21 May 2013 }}</ref>
==Brief Summary==
'''''India Becoming''''', by the [[Harvard University]] trained social anthropologist, Akash Kapur, is an in-depth study of simple average people from a nondescript town in [[South India]], their mundane life and their struggle to survive the vicissitudes of the burgeoning society that modernization has thrown their way. In this debut attempt, Kapur chose to go to such great lengths to depict the real-life stories and experiences of people that it took him five years to finish the book.<ref>{{cite web|last=KARTHIKEYAN|first=Aparna|title=Is India Becoming?|url=http://www.thehindu.com/books/is-india-becoming/article4070652.ece|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=28 May 2013|date=2012-11-06}}</ref>
Kapur, in this critically acclaimed book, also expresses his unbiased sentiments about the outcomes rapid urbanization brings in its wake, affecting people from all social strata, both the country and the bustling metropolis, be it his rural hometown in [[Tamil Nadu]] or the chaotic cities of [[Bombay]], [[Bangalore]] or [[Chennai]]. The real-life characters in his book successfully reflect the writer's views in graphic detail.<ref name=Becoming>{{cite web|last=Pilling|first=David|title=India Becoming|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/c5fb8fca-693d-11e1-9618-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2UWAEpraT|publisher=FINANCIAL TIMES|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>
Born to an Indian father and American mother, Kapur's early life was spent in [[India]]. He left for US when he was 16 and started his academic years there. He came back to India in 2003 to settle down permanently. "I was coming home, but in many ways, it was to a home I didn't recognize anymore" says the one-time "Letter From India" columnist for the [[International Herald Tribune]] and the [[New York Times]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Akash Kapur: India Becoming|url=http://thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2012-03-20/akash-kapur-india-becoming|publisher=The Diane Rehm Show|accessdate=28 May 2013|date=2012-03-20|}}</ref> A book of hybrid nonfiction, ''India Becoming'' presents an imagined geography of 2010s Delhi and India as experienced and created by an Indian returnee migrant author.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|last2=Lau|first2=Lisa|date=2018|title=The conjunctural spaces of ‘new India’: imagined geographies of 2010s India in representations by returnee migrants|url=https://journals.sagepub.com/action/captchaChallenge?redirectUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.sagepub.com%2Fdoi%2F10.1177%2F1474474018786033|journal=cultural geographies|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1177/1474474018786033|issn=1474-4740|via=}}</ref>
As Mendes and Lau argue, Kapur's text reflects "some of the enduring key themes involved in the reinvention and restoration of imagined geographies, such as assimilation vs alienation/anomie and tradition vs modernity."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|last2=Lau|first2=Lisa|date=2018|title=The conjunctural spaces of ‘new India’: imagined geographies of 2010s India in representations by returnee migrants|url=https://journals.sagepub.com/action/captchaChallenge?redirectUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.sagepub.com%2Fdoi%2F10.1177%2F1474474018786033|journal=cultural geographies|language=en|volume=|pages=5|doi=10.1177/1474474018786033|issn=1474-4740|via=}}</ref> To quote an excerpt from his book: "Einstein once wrote of America that its people were "always becoming, never being", but it was in India now that I felt that sense of newness, of perpetual reinvention and forward momentum that I had felt when I first moved to America".<ref name=Akash>{{cite web|last=Rasul|first=Nadia|title=Book Excerpt: 'India Becoming' by Akash Kapur|url=http://asiasociety.org/blog/asia/book-excerpt-india-becoming-akash-kapur|publisher=Asia Society|accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>
